Introduction

We have chosen to analyse data from multiple databases that contain information about the happiness at work. Originally, this study was dedicated to understanding the relationship between the happiness at work and the turnover rates. The data was collected from 37 companies based on Barcelona. To collect this data, the researches created an app that allowed employees to evaluate their companies by giving a vote ranging from 1 to 4. After voting, the employees were invited to see the commentaries and the votes from their peers. Thus, they were allowed to react by liking or disliking the commentary.

The data have been analysed by diverse data scientists and they normally concludes that it does not seem to have a relationship between the variable. However, are there more information that could we extract from this interesting database?

In this study, we will first analyse and understand the 4 databases provided (churn, commentinteractions, commentclean and votes). Then, we will explore visually some characteristics of the employees based on the data provided like: the mean happiness based on the mean vote and the relationship between feedback and turnover. In the end, we will answer our main question: are the radical votes (the highest and the lowest) the ones that generate more interaction?

So, to begin our study, let’s attribute an object to each database:

Understanding the negative values in employee column in Churn

The first thing that caught our attention was the presence of employees represented by negative IDs. Why have they negative IDs? To answer that question, we have began by looking at the quantity of employees with Negative IDs.

Conclusion1 : There are 214 employees with negative values

To continue our analysis, we decided to test the hypothesis of a relationship between be churned (quit the company) and having negative value ID. To proceed with this test, we have counted the quantity of employees with negative IDs that are still on the company and those of employees with negative IDs that are still on the company.

churn %>%
  filter(employee < 0) %>%
  count(stillExists)
## # A tibble: 1 × 2
##   stillExists     n
##   <lgl>       <int>
## 1 FALSE         429
churn %>%
  filter(employee > 0) %>%
  count(stillExists)
## # A tibble: 2 × 2
##   stillExists     n
##   <lgl>       <int>
## 1 FALSE         745
## 2 TRUE         3673

Conclusion2: Inconclusive

Our first hypothesis was proved false. According to the first table, every single employee who has a negative ID is not in the company anymore. However, when we look at the second table, we verify that there are also employees with positive ID that are not anymore in the company

Therefore, we have decided to filter the negative values of the DataBase Churn and to create some new objects

churn_positive <- churn %>%
  filter(employee > 0)

churn_positive_join <- churn %>%
  filter(employee > 0) %>%
  na.omit() %>%
  group_by(employee) %>%
  summarise(sum(numVotes))

churn_positive_main <- churn %>%
  filter(employee >0) %>%
  left_join(churn_positive_join)
## Joining, by = "employee"

Is the majority of employees happy at their works based on their votes?

To answer this question, we have decided to work with a boxplot visualization. This type of plot allows us to notice easily the out liners and also where lies the majority of the distribution. To use this representation, we proceeded to a Data Wrangling of the votes database to calculate the mean vote and thus the mean happiness.

votes_mean <- votes %>%
  group_by(employee) %>%
  summarise(mean(vote))
names(votes_mean)[2] <- 'mean_vote'

Graph: Mean Happiness

## Conclusion 4: Analyzing this graph, we can notice that the majority of the distribution is located between 2.5 and 3.5. In that case, we can conclude that in average the employees who participated on these research were happy inside their companies. However, it is interesting to see that the majority of the outliers lies between 1 and 2.

The most active employees are those who stay or quit the company?

Considering that the majority of employees seems happy at their companies. Is the turnover high in the companies we study? To understand that, we have conceived a graph.

Graphiques Turnover et Feedback et tournouver

##Conclusion 5: The graph shows us that clearly the majority of the employees are still on their respective companies. Considering that participating on the research was not mandatory and that many employees have decided to do not vote, we can ask ourselves if there is a relationship between staying on the company and participating on the research. In other words, are the employees who gave feedback (voted) on this research more inclination to quit or to stay on the company (even considering that they can note negatively) ?

To answer this question, we generated a graph with three variables: Votes per Employee, Employee Id and Still Exists (left the company or not).

#Conclusion6: The interesting graph created shows us that the employees labeled with a blue triangle (employees who are still on the company), are also those that voted more. This shows a possible relationship between giving feedback and not leaving the company.

The next question we attempt to answer is the main question of our work. Is there a relationship between the vote and the reactions created?

To answer that question we will test some hypothesis. The first one is that the extreme votes (1 or 4) generates more reactions than average votes (2 and 3) since people will have a tendency to disagree with them. So to test that hypothesis we will create a new object (votes_reactions) that will serve as the basis of the next objects we will create to generate 3 graphs.

votes_reactions <- votes %>%
  left_join(commentclean) %>%
  select(vote, commentId, likes, dislikes) %>%
  na.omit()
## Joining, by = c("employee", "companyAlias")
votes_reactions$reactions <- votes_reactions$likes + votes_reactions$dislikes

Reactions (Likes + Dislikes) per vote

votes_reactions_total <- votes_reactions %>%
  group_by(vote) %>%
  summarise(sum(reactions))
names(votes_reactions_total)[2] <- 'reactions_total'

Graph: Total Reactions per type of vote

Conclusion7

Our hypothesis does not seem completely incorrect. Although the vote that has produced more reactions was 3, 4 and 1 were respectively second and third. The vote that generates much less reactions than the others is 2. However, does that mean that people agree more with the vote 3 or disagree ?

Let’s analyse first the agreement (likes) and then the disagreement (dislikes)

Likes per vote: Data Wrangling

votes_reactions_likes <- votes_reactions %>%
  group_by(vote) %>%
  summarise(sum(likes))
names(votes_reactions_likes)[2] <- 'likes_total'

Graph: Total Likes per Vote

##Conclusion8 We notice that the Total Likes per vote graphs is very similar to the Total reactions per vote graph. The difference lies on the value of likes received by vote 1. This suggests that vote 1 receives more dislikes than likes since it has reduced its value significantly.

However, what about dislikes per vote?

Dislikes per vote: Data Wrangling

votes_reactions_dislikes <- votes_reactions %>%
  group_by(vote) %>%
  summarise(sum(dislikes))
names(votes_reactions_dislikes)[2] <- 'dislikes_total'

Graph dislikes per type of vote:

##Conclusion9 This graph provide us with interesting conclusions. It seems that even considering that the vote type three generated more reactions (Likes + Dislikes), the vote 4 was the most disliked and the quantity of dislikes of vote 1 is significantly higher than the quantity of likes of vote 1. That means that there is a trend to disagree more than agree with radical votes 1 or 4. Also, considering that the average vote of the employees was around 2.5 and 3.5, it seems that there is a trend to agree with the vote gave by the majority: 3.
